Megan Napoli describes 1955 to 2018 weather and amphibian phenology at Mohonk preserve. Earlier calling in wood frogs, earlier egg laying in spotted salamanders. Associated with warmer weather. Amazing data set! # jmih18

This is the Wood Frog. The NYS Senate recently voted to make this cute little guy our official State Amphibian! Meanwhile, in NY where there are no other serious problems to address, the state legislature has been debating whether or not the wood frog should be the official state amphibian for FIVE YEARS. https://twitter.com/mahoneyw/status/1007321671215304704 …

The Senate is passing the bill making the wood frog the official state amphibian. "For the record, there are much more attractive opinions in NYS," says Sen. Liz Krueger. "There’s quite a few newts I looked up."

@ LizKrueger said she’ll vote for @ JohnDeFrancisco’s bill making Wood Frogs the official amphibian of NY... but under protest because prettier amphibians exist. DeFran reminded the room this was brought to him by a 4th grade class: “Now they can see that government does work.”
S3502, sponsored by @ JohnDeFrancisco, passed 56-3 (unofficial). Names the wood frog the official amphibian of the State of New York. https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/bills/2017/s3502 …

Perhaps I jumped the gun. Senate Rules just reported to the floor S3502, making the wood frog the official # NYS amphibian. Bill sponsor @ JohnDeFrancisco says it's a "lesson in govt" for 4th grade class in Skaneateles NY that came up with the idea.

text: Don't let its cuteness fool you. This red-spotted newt will grow up to be an amphibian-eater. Right now they are eating our salamander embryos and wood frog tadpoles. Newts begin life in water, are teenagers on land, and return to water as adults # GoOutside # BeAFieldBiologistpic.twitter.com/TAMz4Cxj0q
